issue.title: Add support for Python 3.8+ on Windows when CUDA is enabled

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: Enable using onnxruntime-gpu on Windows with Python 3.8+

**Motivation and Context**
- Due to a breaking change in Python 3.8 the system PATH is no longer searched when loading a DLL. This prevented loading of CUDA and cuDNN DLLs.
- In Python 3.8+ this is handled by explicitly adding the path to DLLs using `os.add_dll_directory()`.
- CUDA Toolkit is expected to be installed on the system by using NVIDIA's official installer.
- cuDNN is expected to be installed on the system by following the [official installation instructions](https://docs.nvidia.com/deeplearning/cudnn/install-guide/index.html#install-windows), i.e. to be at the same location as CUDA Toolkit.
- CUDA/cuDNN version is currently hard-coded to default versions used in CI. Supporting any version would require broader changes in the code.

body: why did we hardcode CUDA 10.2 instead of just checking CUDA_PATH which gets set after a proper CUDA installation on Windows?

When multiple versions of CUDA Toolkit are installed on the system CUDA_PATH might point to the wrong version.

This could be solved in a generic way by having a .py file (generated during CMake build) which contains the CUDA version. It could be then imported from onnxruntime/python/_pybind_state.py. This would allow referencing the CUDA version used to build the package.

> When multiple versions of CUDA Toolkit are installed on the system CUDA_PATH might point to the wrong version.
> 
> This could be solved in a generic way by having a .py file (generated during CMake build) which contains the CUDA version. It could be then imported from onnxruntime/python/_pybind_state.py. This would allow referencing the CUDA version used to build the package.

Simpler to just respect CUDA_PATH
That is the purpose of CUDA_PATH. you should set CUDA_PATH to the version of CUDA that you want to use if you have multiple versions installed.
e.g. see: https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/switch-different-versions-of-cuda-in-win10/54999

your suggestion has merit though, if we want to validate the proper dependencies exists on the deployment target.

body: As of version 1.6.0, **onnxruntime-gpu** Python package relies at runtime on PATH (Python 3.7 and earlier) or CUDA_PATH (Python 3.8 and newer), so it is possible to build and use it with either CUDA 10.x or 11.x, assuming the relevant environment variable is set correctly.
